Though full of obvious errors in copying, they are free from deliberate corrections ; all three however are muti- lated, and they leave considerable gaps in the text unattested. The same is the case with a more numerous second set, of the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries, which are manifestly based on one or other of the above or on their common source. A third set, all of a later date, give a complete text ; but they do not show the same amount of agreement as the two earlier groups, and also their value is even more reduced by the probability that they have been largely corrupted by conj eetural emendation.
